What is Django?

Django is a high-level, open-source Python web framework that enables developers to build secure, scalable, 

and maintainable web applications rapidly.

It follows the MVT (Modelâ€“Viewâ€“Template) architectural pattern and includes many batteries-included features such as:

ORM (Object-Relational Mapper)

Authentication system

Admin interface

URL routing

Form handling

Security features (CSRF protection, XSS protection, SQL injection prevention)

Caching, middleware, sessions, and more

Djangoâ€™s philosophy is "Don't Repeat Yourself" (DRY) and "batteries included", meaning it ships with almost 

everything needed for modern web development.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are the key features of Django?

Django is a high-level Python web framework with several powerful features, including:

MVT Architecture â€“ Clean separation of data, logic, and presentation.

Built-in ORM â€“ Allows database operations using Python instead of SQL.

Auto-generated Admin Panel â€“ Ready-to-use backend dashboard.

Strong Security â€“ Protection against CSRF, XSS, SQL injection, etc.

Batteries-Included â€“ Comes with authentication, routing, forms, sessions, caching, and more.

Scalability â€“ Suitable for high-traffic apps like Instagram.

URL Routing System â€“ Clean and maintainable URL configuration.

Excellent Documentation â€“ Easy to learn and well-maintained.

Large Ecosystem â€“ Many third-party packages (e.g., DRF, Channels).

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Explain Djangoâ€™s MVT Architecture.

Django follows the MVT architecture, which stands for Modelâ€“Viewâ€“Template. It works like this:

Model

Handles the data layer. It defines the database structure and interacts with the ORM.

View:

Contains the business logic. It processes requests, fetches data from the model, and sends the data to the template.

Template:

Responsible for the presentation layer. It displays the data to the user using HTML with Django template tags.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is a Django Model?

A Django model is a Python class that represents a table in the database. Each attribute of the class corresponds to a database field, 

and Django automatically creates the table structure using migrations.

Models allow you to interact with the database using Djangoâ€™s ORM, so you can perform operations like create, read, 

update, delete without writing SQL manually.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is a QuerySet in Django?

A QuerySet is a collection of data retrieved from the database using Djangoâ€™s ORM. 

It represents a set of objects and allows you to filter, sort, slice, and query data efficiently.

QuerySets are lazy, meaning Django doesn't hit the database until the data is actually needed.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the difference between get() and filter() in Django ORM?

get() returns a single object that matches the query.

If no object or more than one object is found, it raises an error.

filter() returns a QuerySet (multiple objects) and never raises an error, even if the result is empty.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are Django views?

Django views are Python functions or class-based methods that handle incoming requests and return responses.

They contain the business logic of your applicationâ€”fetching data from the model, processing it, and passing it to templates or returning JSON.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are Django templates?

Django templates are HTML files that allow you to display dynamic data using Djangoâ€™s template language.

They separate the presentation layer from the business logic.

Templates support variables, filters, loops, conditions, and template inheritance.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is manage.py used for?	

manage.py is a command-line utility that helps you interact with your Django project.

It allows you to run commands like starting the server, creating apps, running migrations, creating superusers, and more.

It automatically sets the correct DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE for your project so you donâ€™t have to configure it manually.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you create a Django project and app?

To create a Django project, you use the django-admin startproject command.

To create an app inside that project, you use the python manage.py startapp command.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the purpose of settings.py?

settings.py contains all the configuration for your Django project.

This includes database settings, installed apps, middleware, static files configuration, templates, security keys, allowed hosts, and more.

It is the central place where Django reads project-wide settings during startup.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is urls.py? (Interview Answer)

urls.py is the file in Django where you define the URL routing for your project or app.

It maps URLs (like /home/, /products/) to views, so Django knows which view to execute when a user visits a particular URL.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you connect Django with a database?

Django connects to a database through the DATABASES setting inside settings.py.

You just specify the database engine, name, user, password, host, and port.

Django uses this configuration to automatically handle migrations and ORM queries.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are static files in Django?

Static files are files that donâ€™t change dynamically and are served as-is.

Examples include CSS, JavaScript, images, fonts, etc.

Django provides a static files framework to help you collect and serve these assets during development and production.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are media files in Django?

Media files are user-uploaded files such as images, videos, documents, and audio.

They are different from static files because static files are for the project (CSS/JS), while media files come from users.

Django allows you to configure a media directory and serve uploaded files during development.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the Django admin site?

The Django admin site is a built-in, automatically generated backend interface that allows you to manage your projectâ€™s data.

It provides CRUD operations for your models without writing any code.

You can add, edit, delete, and search records easily.

Itâ€™s mainly used by developers and staffâ€”not end users.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is urlpatterns?

urlpatterns is a Python list in urls.py that contains all the URL routes of your Django project or app.

Each entry in the list maps a URL path to a specific view.

Django checks this list to decide which view should handle an incoming request.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is a Django Form?

A Django form is a Python class used to handle user input, such as data from HTML forms.

Forms help with validation, error handling, and cleaning input before saving it to the database.

Django provides both:

Forms â†’ manually define form fields

ModelForms â†’ automatically create a form from a model

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the difference between Django Form and ModelForm? (Interview Answer)

Django Form:

You manually define every field. It is not linked to any model.

Useful for custom input that doesn't directly map to a database table.

ModelForm:

Automatically creates form fields based on a Django model.

Saves data directly to the database with .save().
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How does Django handle sessions?

Django handles sessions by storing session data on the server and saving only a session ID in the userâ€™s browser as a cookie.

This allows Django to keep track of each userâ€™s data across multiple requests (like login info, cart items, preferences).

Django uses its built-in session middleware and supports several storage backends:

Database (default)

Cache

File-based

Signed cookies

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is Django middleware?

Django middleware is a lightweight processing layer that sits between the request and response cycle.

It allows you to process requests before they reach the view and process responses before they reach the browser.

Middleware is used for tasks such as:

Authentication

Session handling

CSRF protection

Caching

Request/response logging

Custom security checks

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How can you create custom middleware?

You create custom middleware by writing a Python callable (usually a class) that intercepts requests and/or responses, 

implement the appropriate hooks (process_request, process_view, process_exception, process_response) or the new __call__-based interface,

and then add the middleware path to MIDDLEWARE in settings.py.

Middleware is used for global cross-cutting concerns like logging, auth checks, headers, rate-limiting, maintenance mode, etc.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is context in Django templates?

Context is a dictionary of data that you pass from a view to a template.

The template uses this context to display dynamic content.

In other words, context is how views send data to the HTML page.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are template inheritance and template tags?

Template Inheritance

Template inheritance in Django allows you to create a base template (with common layout like header, footer, navbar) and 

let child templates override only specific blocks.

It helps avoid repeating HTML and keeps templates clean and maintainable.

Template Tags

Template tags are special Django commands used inside templates for:

loops

conditions

loading static files

including templates

custom logic

They add dynamic behavior inside HTML pages.


_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the reverse() function in Django?

The reverse() function is used to get the URL of a view by its name, instead of hardcoding the URL path.

It helps avoid broken links when URLs change and is commonly used in redirects, templates, and class-based views.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is select_related and prefetch_related?

Both select_related and prefetch_related are Django ORM optimization methods used to 

reduce the number of database queries when working with related models

1. select_related

Used for foreign key and one-to-one relationships.

Performs a SQL JOIN and fetches related objects in one query.

Faster for single-valued relationships.

2. prefetch_related

Used for many-to-many and reverse foreign key relations.

Performs two separate queries and merges results in Python.

Ideal for lists/collections of related objects.
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is a Django Signal? (Interview Answer)

A Django signal is a notification system that allows certain parts of your application to get automatically notified 

when specific actions happenâ€”such as object creation, update, deletion, or user login.

Signals help you run code automatically when an event occurs, without modifying the core logic.

Common built-in signals:

post_save

pre_save

post_delete

user_logged_in

user_logged_out
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you implement user authentication in Django?

Django provides a built-in authentication system. You implement authentication by using the built-in User model (or a custom AUTH_USER_MODEL), 

the authenticate() and login() helpers, and decorators/mixins like login_required / LoginRequiredMixin. 

For common flows you can use UserCreationForm (registration) and AuthenticationForm (login). Use logout() to sign out. 

Protect views with permissions or groups when needed.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you override Djangoâ€™s default User model?

You override Djangoâ€™s default User model by creating a custom user model using either:

AbstractUser â†’ Extend the existing User model (recommended, most common)

AbstractBaseUser â†’ Build your own user model from scratch (advanced)

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are class-based views (CBVs)?

Class-Based Views (CBVs) are Django views written as Python classes instead of functions.

They provide reusable logic by offering built-in methods for common tasks like listing objects, displaying details, 

creating, updating, and deleting records.

CBVs help you write cleaner, organized, and reusable code by using inheritance and mixins.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the difference between ListView and DetailView?

ListView is used to display a list of objects, while DetailView is used to display the details of a single object.

ListView â†’ returns multiple objects (QuerySet)

DetailView â†’ returns one object (based on id/slug/pk)

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How to upload files in Django?

Use a FileField or ImageField on a model, accept files in a form (make sure the form uses enctype="multipart/form-data"), handle request.

FILES in the view (or use a ModelForm), and configure MEDIA_ROOT/MEDIA_URL in settings.py. In development, 

serve media via django.conf.urls.static.static. For production, use a proper media storage (S3, CDN) and validate file size/type.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you implement pagination?

Use Djangoâ€™s pagination utilities. For generic views set paginate_by on a ListView. 

For function-based views use django.core.paginator.Paginator to split a queryset into pages and read the page number from the request (?page=2). 

Always handle invalid page numbers (EmptyPage, PageNotAnInteger).

In short: use ListView.paginate_by for quick setup or Paginator for custom control.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the Django ORM?

The Django ORM (Objectâ€“Relational Mapper) allows you to interact with the database using Python code instead of SQL.

It converts Python model operations into SQL queries automatically.

You can create, retrieve, update, and delete records without writing any SQL manually.

It supports multiple databases like PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, Oracle, and makes switching databases easy.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How to perform raw SQL queries in Django?

Django allows raw SQL queries using three main approaches:

Model.objects.raw() â†’ for SELECT queries that map to a model

connection.cursor() â†’ for executing INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, or custom SQL

Extra() (deprecated) â†’ not recommended anymore

Even when using raw SQL, Django still protects against SQL injection using query parameters.
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is a slug and how is it used?

A slug is a URL-friendly string (usually derived from a title) used to create clean, readable, SEO-friendly URLs.

It contains only letters, numbers, hyphens, and underscores.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are the different types of model relationships?

Django supports three main types of model relationships:

One-to-One Relationship â†’ OneToOneField

One-to-Many Relationship â†’ ForeignKey

Many-to-Many Relationship â†’ ManyToManyField

These relationships define how models connect to each other in the database.
_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the difference between null=True and blank=True?

null=True â†’ Database-level

It means the database column can store NULL.

Used for non-string fields (Integer, Date, ForeignKey, etc.)

blank=True â†’ Validation-level

It means the field can be left empty in forms (admin, Django forms, ModelForms).

Used when you want the form to accept empty input.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is caching in Django?

Caching in Django means storing frequently-used data in memory (or another fast storage) so that future requests can be served quickly 

without hitting the database each time.

Django provides multiple caching backends like Memcached, Redis, file-based cache, and local-memory cache.

Caching improves performance, reduces database load, and speeds up page rendering.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is Django REST Framework (DRF)?

Django REST Framework (DRF) is a powerful and flexible toolkit for building Web APIs in Django.

It provides an easy way to serialize data, handle authentication, create API endpoints, and support features like pagination, permissions, 

filters, and browsable API interfaces.

DRF makes it simple to build RESTful APIs that interact with mobile apps, front-end frameworks (React, Angular, Vue), and other services.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the difference between WSGI and ASGI in Django?

WSGI and ASGI are two different server interfaces used by Django to handle requests.

ðŸ”µ WSGI (Web Server Gateway Interface)

Older, traditional interface

Supports only synchronous (blocking) requests

Used for classic Django apps before Django 3.0

Works well for typical web pages and APIs

ðŸŸ¢ ASGI (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface)

Modern interface

Supports both synchronous and asynchronous requests

Enables real-time features: WebSockets, long-polling, async tasks

Django supports ASGI from version 3.0+

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How does Django handle asynchronous views?

Django (3.1+) supports asynchronous views, allowing you to write views using async def.

These views run on Djangoâ€™s ASGI layer and let you perform non-blocking operations such as calling async APIs, making async database 

queries (when supported), or running long I/O tasks without blocking the server.

Django automatically detects whether a view is synchronous or asynchronous and handles them appropriately.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Explain how Djangoâ€™s ORM handles transactions.

Djangoâ€™s ORM automatically wraps each HTTP request inside a transaction when ATOMIC_REQUESTS is enabled, or you can manually control transactions 

using transaction.atomic().

If everything inside the block runs successfully, Django commits the changes to the database; if an exception occurs, Django rolls back the entire 

block to keep data consistent.

Django guarantees ACID properties: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are database migrations? How do they work internally?

Database migrations in Django are a way to keep your database schema in sync with your models.

Whenever you change a model (add a field, delete a model, rename a column), Django generates a migration file that describes the changes.

You apply these changes to the actual database using:

python manage.py makemigrations

python manage.py migrate

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What is the role of Celery in Django?

Celery is a distributed task queue used in Django to run background tasks asynchronously, outside the normal requestâ€“response cycle.

It is perfect for tasks that take time (email sending, PDF generation, API calls, image processing) so they donâ€™t block the user or slow down your app.

Celery works with a message broker (RabbitMQ or Redis) and Django acts as the producer sending tasks to workers.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How do you secure a Django application?

Secure a Django app by running with DEBUG=False, using HTTPS, protecting secrets, enabling Djangoâ€™s security settings/cookies/CSRF protections, 

validating inputs, hardening auth, limiting access (admin/IP/rate-limit), keeping dependencies and Django up-to-date, and monitoring/logging for 

attacks.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

How does Django handle cross-site request forgery (CSRF)?

Django protects against CSRF attacks using the CSRF middleware and a unique CSRF token.

This token is added to every form that performs POST requests. When the form is submitted, Django checks if the token matches the one stored 

in the userâ€™s session.

If the token is missing, invalid, or tampered with, Django blocks the request.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are custom model managers?

Custom model managers in Django allow you to add extra query methods or customize the default queryset for a model.

They help organize repeated database logic in one place instead of writing the same filters in multiple views.

Every Django model has a default manager called objects, but you can override it or create additional managers.

_____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

What are signals vs observers? When to use or avoid them?

Custom model managers in Django allow you to add extra query methods or customize the default queryset for a model.

They help organize repeated database logic in one place instead of writing the same filters in multiple views.

Every Django model has a default manager called objects, but you can override it or create additional managers.

